KI wird den digitalen Raum nicht demokratisieren – sie wird ihn effizienter privatisieren. (- JD Koehler)


Artificial Intelligence and the Missing Public Square

Draft by JD Köhler

Artificial intelligence is widely described as a turning point — a technological force that will reshape economies, redefine governance and perhaps even renew democratic life. The scale of expectation is striking. So is the underlying assumption: that A.I., by virtue of its sophistication, will correct or at least rebalance the deficiencies of the digital age.

That assumption deserves scrutiny.

Before asking what artificial intelligence will do to society, it is necessary to ask a prior question, one that is at once simpler and more consequential: Into what kind of space is A.I. being introduced?

The answer is rarely stated plainly. Yet it is decisive. Artificial intelligence does not emerge in a neutral environment. It is layered onto a digital infrastructure that has developed over decades, shaped not by democratic design but by market incentives. The architecture of the digital world — the spaces in which communication, visibility and interaction occur — is overwhelmingly private, fragmented and optimized for extraction rather than participation.

If that premise holds, then the implications are difficult to ignore. A.I. will not, by itself, democratize the digital realm. It will, far more likely, render its existing structure more efficient.

⸻

The dominant discourse on digitalization has long been preoccupied with the interface between state and citizen: how public services can be digitized, how administrative processes can be streamlined, how access can be improved. These are legitimate concerns, but they address only one dimension of democratic life.

Democracy does not begin at the moment of formal interaction with institutions. It begins earlier, in the quotidian exchanges through which trust is established and maintained among citizens. These exchanges are not procedural; they are spatial. They occur in environments that make visibility, encounter and reciprocity possible.

In the physical world, such environments are ubiquitous and largely taken for granted: streets, squares, parks, markets — places that are neither fully structured nor fully controlled, but open enough to allow for unplanned interaction. Their defining characteristic is not efficiency but accessibility. They are not optimized for profit, nor are they governed by opaque mechanisms of distribution. They are, in a meaningful sense, public.

The digital world lacks an equivalent.

What has emerged in its place is not a digital public sphere in the classical sense, but a constellation of privately owned platforms. These platforms provide the functional appearance of public space — they host communication, enable visibility, facilitate exchange — yet they do so under conditions that are fundamentally different. Access is mediated, attention is allocated algorithmically and interaction is continuously measured, analyzed and monetized.

The result is not the disappearance of social interaction, but its transformation. Individuals continue to meet, communicate and coordinate. But they do so as users within proprietary systems, not as citizens within a shared public domain.

⸻

This structural shift becomes most apparent not in moments of crisis or high politics, but in the ordinary fabric of daily life.

A misplaced object, a request for assistance, a local announcement — situations that in a physical setting would rely on a common space of visibility instead become dependent on platform-specific channels. Information circulates, but not universally; it is confined to networks, groups or algorithmic pathways that are neither transparent nor collectively governed.

These are minor failures, easily overlooked. Yet they point to a deeper absence: the absence of a digital environment in which communication can occur without prior affiliation, without payment for visibility and without subjection to external optimization.

In other words, the absence of a digital public square.

⸻

It is into this environment that artificial intelligence is now being deployed.

The prevailing narrative suggests that A.I. will introduce a new layer of intelligence into digital systems, enabling more informed decision-making, more equitable distribution of information and more responsive governance. Such outcomes are conceivable in principle. In practice, however, A.I. operates within existing structures. It does not redefine their underlying logic; it enhances their operational capacity.

In platform-based environments, this means improving the precision of targeting, the accuracy of prediction and the efficiency of monetization. It means refining the mechanisms through which attention is captured and behavior is anticipated. It means, in effect, intensifying the very dynamics that have shaped the digital landscape to date.

The consequence is not a transition from private to public space, but a deepening of privatization.

Artificial intelligence, in this context, functions less as a corrective than as an accelerant.

⸻

This conclusion is not a judgment on the technology itself. Artificial intelligence is not intrinsically aligned with any particular social outcome. Its effects depend on the structures into which it is integrated.

In a system oriented toward public value, A.I. could support democratic processes, enhance accessibility and strengthen collective decision-making. In a system oriented toward extraction, it will amplify those tendencies.

At present, the digital environment largely reflects the latter orientation.

⸻

The implications for democracy are subtle but significant.

Democratic systems depend not only on formal procedures — elections, deliberation, representation — but also on informal social conditions. Among these, trust occupies a central position. Not trust as an abstract principle, but as an emergent property of repeated, everyday interactions among individuals.

Such interactions require spaces in which they can occur. Spaces that are sufficiently open to allow for encounter, sufficiently stable to sustain continuity and sufficiently neutral to avoid systematic distortion.

In their absence, the formation of trust becomes more difficult. Social connections fragment, visibility becomes uneven and the capacity for collective understanding diminishes.

Political theorists have long described this phenomenon in terms of “social capital”: the network of relationships and norms that enable cooperation within a society. When the spaces that support these networks erode, the resilience of democratic institutions is gradually undermined.

The digital realm, as currently constituted, does little to replenish this form of capital.

⸻

Much of the contemporary debate on digital democracy focuses on formal innovation: digital participation platforms, online consultations, new mechanisms of civic engagement. These initiatives address important aspects of institutional design. Yet they operate downstream of a more fundamental condition.

They presuppose the existence of a shared space in which citizens can encounter one another as equals.

Without such a space, participation becomes procedural rather than relational. It may produce outcomes, but it does not necessarily sustain the underlying fabric of democratic life.

⸻

The question that emerges is therefore not primarily technological.

It is architectural.

Do we intend to construct a digital environment that includes genuinely public spaces? Spaces that are not contingent on platform ownership, not governed by opaque algorithms and not dependent on the commodification of attention?

If democracy were to be designed today, from first principles, it is difficult to imagine that such spaces would be omitted. And yet, in the evolution of the digital world, they have been.

Artificial intelligence will not resolve this omission. It will operate within it.

Indeed, by increasing the efficiency and scale of existing systems, it may render the consequences more pronounced and more difficult to reverse.

⸻

The future of democratic societies will not be determined solely by the capabilities of their technologies. It will be shaped, more fundamentally, by the environments in which those technologies are embedded.

Intelligence, whether human or artificial, requires a space in which to act.

At present, that space remains, in the digital realm, overwhelmingly private.
